{{spice}}
[[Image:Parsley Flat.jpg|right|thumb|Flat leaf parsley]] [[Image:Parsley Curled.jpg|right|thumb|Curly leaf parsley]]
'''Parsley''' is a bright green, biennial herb that is very common in Middle Eastern, European, and American cooking. Its value as a breath-freshener, and much of its taste, come from its high concentration of chlorophyll. It is also high in [[Cookbook:Vitamins|vitamin]] C.
Two forms of parsley are used as herbs: curly leaf and Italian or flat leaf. Curly leaf parsley is often used as a [[Cookbook:Garnish|garnish]]. Many people think flat leaf parsley has a stronger flavor, and it is sometimes used as a substitute for [[Cookbook:Cilantro|coriander leaves]]. Its flat leaves are less springy than those of curly leaf parsley, and hence it is easier to chop. Another type of parsley, Hamburg parsley, is grown for its edible root, similar in appearance to a [[Cookbook:Parsnip|parsnip]].
{{Wikipedia|Parsley}}
[[hy:Եփութուխ:Մաղադանոս]] [[nl:Kookboek/Peterselie]]

{{spice}}

'''Mint''' refers to the leaves of a perennial herb, typically [[Cookbook:Peppermint|peppermint]] (''Mentha piperita'') or [[Cookbook:Spearmint|spearmint]] (''Mentha spicata''), used for flavoring in [[Cookbook:Candy|candy]], [[Cookbook:Tea|teas]], and some dishes. An extract is produced for uses where the leaves would be inconvenient.

Mint is also regarded as a good accompaniment to roast [[Cookbook:Lamb|lamb]], especially in the form of [[Cookbook:Mint sauce|mint sauce]].

{{Wikipedia|Mint}}

{{cookstub}}

== Formulae == You are expected to know the following formulae, as they will not be provided in the formula book:
<math> a = \frac{dv}{dt} = \frac{dv}{dx} \frac{dx}{dt} = v \frac{dv}{dx} </math>
{{BookCat|filing=deep}}

When you want to say that something exists, there two verbs you have to choose from depending on whether the subject is an ''animate-'' or ''inanimate object''. The difference is not quite living/non-living, as plants would be considered inanimate (as they don't move ... well, most only really slowly). A fish swimming in its fish-bowl would be an animate object, but a dead fish (whether at the fish-mongers or — let's hope not — in its bowl) would be in-animate.

* For '''animate''' objects (humans and animals), use "いる" (polite present positive: "います").
* For '''inanimate''' objects, use "ある" (polite present positive: "あります").

Note that these can denote both presence or possession.

In the dialogues below, you may replace "います" with "あります".

== Dialogue ==
=== The presence of no particular object ===
{{Japanese conversation|begin}}
{{Japanese conversation
| japanese= 何かいますか。
| english = Is something (animate) there?
}}
{{Japanese conversation
| japanese= <animate object> がいます。
| english = There's a <animate object>.
}}
{{Japanese conversation
| japanese= 何もいません。 (なにも　いません)
| english = There's nothing.
}}
{{Japanese conversation|end}}

=== To ask about the presence of a particular animate object ===
{{Japanese conversation|begin}}
{{Japanese conversation
| japanese= <object> がいますか。
| english = Is there a <animate object>?
}}
{{Japanese conversation
| japanese= はい、います。
| english = Yes, it's there.
}}
{{Japanese conversation
| japanese= いいえ、いません。
| english = No, it's not there.
}}
{{Japanese conversation|end}}

If the animate object in question is not present but something else is, you can suggest this by saying:
{{Japanese conversation|begin}}
{{Japanese conversation
| japanese=いいえ、<animate object> はいません。
| english = No, <animate object> is not there.
}}
{{Japanese conversation|end}}

Notice that this reply uses "は" instead of "が". The "は" particle can be translated as "as for such and such", while "が" directly marks the subject.{{citation needed}}

== Vocabulary ==
{{furi|何|なに}}か: "anything/something".
{{furi|何|なに}}も: "everything/nothing" (positive/negative depends on the verb)

